f explicit commentary, presenting themselves as historians or inscribing their works in an English historical tradition. By responding to other varieties of history in this self-conscious way, writers like Andrew Marvell, John Dryden, Delarivier Manley, Daniel Defoe and John Evelyn were able to pioneer influential new techniques for representing their nation’s past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literaturey17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and historyzGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aLiterature and historyzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aDaniel Defoe.  aEnglish historiography.  aJohn Dryden.  aJohn Oldmixon.  aRestoration writers.  aartes historicae.  abiography.  aearly-eighteenth-century writers.  ahistorical literatures.  ajournal.  aletter.  amemoir.  anarrative voices.  aneoclassical ideal.  asatire.  ascandal chronicle.  asecret history.1 aGallagher, Noelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez9783111283630oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526130167423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526130167/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPc1986d2013